1
00:00:10,156 --> 00:00:11,037
Good evening.

2
00:00:11,637 --> 00:00:13,580
I trust you had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:13,800 --> 00:00:17,684
I do not say happy, although I do wish it has been happy.

4
00:00:18,925 --> 00:00:35,082
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

5
00:00:35,637 --> 00:00:44,329
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samasambuddhasa.

6
00:00:44,350 --> 00:00:48,557
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

7
00:00:50,359 --> 00:01:00,393
So we are continuing with our passage through the discourse on the foundations or the establishment of mindfulness.

8
00:01:00,515 --> 00:01:02,116
And we're looking at the body.

9
00:01:02,975 --> 00:01:11,968
The first section is the body, and we've been through the breath, using the breath for mindfulness and seeing mainly in permanence.

10
00:01:12,950 --> 00:01:18,057
The four postures and then full awareness, which basically is daily life practice.

11
00:01:19,299 --> 00:01:24,927
Then we have the body parts to overcome any sense of disgust with the body.

12
00:01:25,528 --> 00:01:28,171
Remember, it's about being disenchanted.

13
00:01:29,602 --> 00:01:36,971
And so there are two more sections, one is called the elements and it was called the nine channel grounds, so these elements.

14
00:01:39,334 --> 00:01:41,718
I think this runs across the ancient world actually.

15
00:01:42,819 --> 00:01:54,513
They say they determine for different characteristics, from which the mind built up some image some feeling etc, etc.

16
00:01:55,287 --> 00:02:12,305
And they were earth, which is to do with pressure and lightness, uh, fire, which is to do with heat, cold, and, uh, and warmth, uh, water, which is elasticity, um, cohesiveness.

17
00:02:12,664 --> 00:02:18,010
So it also is stiffness and, uh, air or wind.

18
00:02:18,050 --> 00:02:22,955
Sometimes it's wind, uh, which is motion or again, stillness.

19
00:02:23,937 --> 00:02:25,057
So, um,

20
00:02:25,830 --> 00:02:30,635
These were meant to be investigated when we actually meditate.

21
00:02:30,816 --> 00:02:38,324
Now, it's pretty clear to see that when we're doing touch, on the feeling of touch.

22
00:02:38,365 --> 00:02:39,786
We'll come to it in a minute.

23
00:02:40,687 --> 00:02:50,076
With eyesight, I mean, it's the subatomic particles, which is quite amazing, really, when you think about it, to be sensitive to subatomic particles.

24
00:02:51,018 --> 00:02:55,483
Photons, light, maybe heat, but it's not really discussed.

25
00:02:55,901 --> 00:03:00,528
The ears definitely pressure, definitely the pressure of sound waves.

26
00:03:00,549 --> 00:03:03,954
And that's actually all you get at the ear drum.

27
00:03:04,014 --> 00:03:05,116
That's the sense base.

28
00:03:05,216 --> 00:03:15,951
Everything else is done by what's known as the mind door or the whole process within the mind itself, turning it into a sound, giving it a meaning, et cetera.

29
00:03:16,774 --> 00:03:23,022
When it comes to taste and smell, that's even more subtle in a way.

30
00:03:23,341 --> 00:03:43,830
I don't think they pertain so clearly to that, although things like pressure, heat, I mean that's obvious when you're eating, but the more subtle sensations I think really aren't explained by these four, but that's just a personal understanding.

31
00:03:44,181 --> 00:03:52,253
If you want to have the traditional understanding, it's in the Visuddhimagga, The Path of Purification by Buddhaghosa.

32
00:03:52,274 --> 00:03:53,876
There's a whole section there if you want it.

33
00:03:54,556 --> 00:03:55,598
So that's a big tome.

34
00:03:55,718 --> 00:04:06,114
It's probably one of the greatest, one of the great spiritual works of the world, of any spiritual tradition.

35
00:04:06,555 --> 00:04:12,383
It holds not only the understanding of the Buddha, but also all the practices

36
00:04:12,852 --> 00:04:14,294
So it's quite a compendium.

37
00:04:15,354 --> 00:04:17,958
You wouldn't want to read it from the first page to the end.

38
00:04:18,017 --> 00:04:20,660
There's about a thousand pages.

39
00:04:21,682 --> 00:04:29,089
But as an encyclopedia of spiritual practice and understanding, it really is quite extraordinary.

40
00:04:29,110 --> 00:04:29,750
Buddhaghosa.

41
00:04:29,769 --> 00:04:35,956
It was compiled, I think, in our Middle Ages, about 500s or so.

42
00:04:36,848 --> 00:04:47,620
Okay, so what it says is that the meditator reviews the same body, however it is placed, however disposed as consisting of elements.

43
00:04:48,401 --> 00:05:02,416
In this body, there's the earth element, the water element, fire element and the earth element, just as though a skilled butcher and his apprentice had killed a cow and was seated at a crossroads with it cut up in pieces.

44
00:05:02,819 --> 00:05:08,226
So to a bhikkhu, a meditator reviews this same body as consisting of the elements.

45
00:05:09,069 --> 00:05:18,704
So just as a butcher, you know, whatever, the leg or the head or whatever, yeah, so you understand that.

46
00:05:19,223 --> 00:05:24,793
So this comes into play when we're practicing vipassana.

47
00:05:26,291 --> 00:05:53,598
so for instance if you have a uh a pain in the knee for instance when you're meditating or discomfort in the in the knee or whatever so as you as it draws your attention you go to it and your first word will be say pain right so you're saying pain this is pain this is what pain feels like and then when you're established there and you make sure that the aversion to the pain has disappeared completely so you're entirely equanimous with the pain

48
00:05:53,848 --> 00:05:56,372
You then, as it were, absorb into the pain.

49
00:05:56,391 --> 00:05:59,415
You go into the pain to deconstruct it, right?

50
00:05:59,696 --> 00:06:04,661
To find out what are the sensations that constitute this concept of pain.

51
00:06:05,142 --> 00:06:12,812
And of course, when you go in there, you'll find things like pressure or heat or a combination of little sensations.

52
00:06:13,694 --> 00:06:19,160
And at that level, of course, there's no concept of pain, so there's no suffering, right?

53
00:06:19,199 --> 00:06:20,581
You've deconstructed it.

54
00:06:21,423 --> 00:06:26,548
So that's the level of direct perception at the sense base.

55
00:06:27,531 --> 00:06:32,036
So this is where the Buddha talks about the point of contact.

56
00:06:32,416 --> 00:06:36,982
For those of you who know dependent origination, the psychology of the Buddha.

57
00:06:37,403 --> 00:06:49,658
So at the point of contact, there has to be an object, there has to be a sense base, so the five senses, including the mind, the sixth sense, because that's the one that the emotions and thoughts appear upon.

58
00:06:49,857 --> 00:06:56,666
and also this basic information from all the other senses appear upon the mind door, as it's called.

59
00:06:57,769 --> 00:07:01,413
And these five these five senses.

60
00:07:03,596 --> 00:07:06,701
I've lost my train of thought there just disappeared.

61
00:07:08,463 --> 00:07:15,274
So he talks about the five senses and and and how how they are

62
00:07:15,490 --> 00:07:16,232
Sorry, that's right.

63
00:07:16,451 --> 00:07:18,997
The object, the sense base and consciousness.

64
00:07:19,059 --> 00:07:23,608
So consciousness is obviously there like a screen upon which this arises.

65
00:07:24,331 --> 00:07:32,250
If it doesn't arise on consciousness, the screen of consciousness, then you don't know it.

66
00:07:32,634 --> 00:07:46,593
I'm sure you've all had the experience of wondering where you got that bruise from or how you cut yourself because your mind was so involved in something you didn't actually notice how you got caught in a door or something or, you know, slight bruise, not a big one.

67
00:07:47,574 --> 00:07:53,201
And that means that that sensation didn't impact on the mind door.

68
00:07:54,663 --> 00:08:01,512
So these four elements are really apparent to us when we

69
00:08:01,745 --> 00:08:31,211
really go into a sensation of feeling now it's the same with an emotion you see deconstructing an emotion what what is an emotion before you give it a name so you might find for instance anxiety or fear for instance and it is in your it's in you you can feel it in your heart and you draw your attention to it and then of course you've got to make sure the fear the fear's gone all the reaction's gone the aversion's gone

70
00:08:31,310 --> 00:08:59,629
and so you're left with the fear then you go into the fear now what what is it you're actually feeling at that sense sensation base you see it's not very much some some watery business some fluidy stuff some pressure and of course by doing that you begin to undermine this fear of the fear when you realize actually it's just a compendium of these sensations okay so it does have a real purpose for insight

71
00:08:59,996 --> 00:09:06,602
And the second thing is, of course, that when you're at that level of perception, impermanence becomes more obvious.

72
00:09:06,764 --> 00:09:09,265
They're just arising and passing away all the time.

73
00:09:11,168 --> 00:09:19,556
So this is an important teaching about elements in the foundations there.

74
00:09:19,576 --> 00:09:29,885
Now, the next one is the channel ground, so it's always interesting this, by the way, in those days, they would just lay the bodies out in an open ground, and as you'll see,

75
00:09:30,254 --> 00:09:34,658
from it that the local animals would eat it, they were shrouded in white.

76
00:09:35,299 --> 00:09:44,570
And it was these cloths that the mendicants, not just the Buddhists, not just the followers of the Buddha, but all mendicants used to take and sew into robes.

77
00:09:45,190 --> 00:09:47,552
And the Buddha simply followed that practice.

78
00:09:49,654 --> 00:09:54,000
Later on, when he had a group of monks and nuns around him,

79
00:09:54,384 --> 00:09:57,889
he wanted them to look a bit more tidy.

80
00:09:58,389 --> 00:10:03,456
So he asked them to cut this cloth in such ways that it recreated a paddy field.

81
00:10:03,916 --> 00:10:08,260
And you can probably see the lines on my robe here at the back here.

82
00:10:08,841 --> 00:10:22,197
So in between the sections there, the paddy fields and the narrow bits of the paths, the raised paths that sort of follow the paddy field round and you can walk around the paddy field.

83
00:10:22,684 --> 00:10:26,130
So you've got a very good robe there, that shows you.

84
00:10:26,150 --> 00:10:31,340
And to then boil them with an arachnid, which gave them a sort of brownie colour.

85
00:10:32,642 --> 00:10:40,696
And then he went on to ask the orders to shave their hair off their head, you see.

86
00:10:40,996 --> 00:10:44,101
So all the others were matted hair.

87
00:10:44,302 --> 00:10:46,164
you know, dreadlocks.

88
00:10:46,225 --> 00:10:53,535
If you see the aesthetics of today that still exist today in India, you'll see that they've got, you know, matlocks.

89
00:10:55,038 --> 00:10:59,065
So it was cooler to have your hair off anyway in that sort of climate.

90
00:10:59,865 --> 00:11:06,275
So I think it was an effort to make his monks and nuns look a bit smart, you might say.

91
00:11:09,326 --> 00:11:16,519
So again, because as though we were seeing a corpse thrown aside in the charnel ground one, two, three days ahead,

92
00:11:16,802 --> 00:11:19,947
Bloated, livid and oozing matter.

93
00:11:20,527 --> 00:11:23,951
Abiku compares this same body with it thus.

94
00:11:24,631 --> 00:11:26,695
This body too is of the same nature.

95
00:11:26,914 --> 00:11:28,015
It will be like that.

96
00:11:28,135 --> 00:11:29,837
It is not exempt from that fate.

97
00:11:30,198 --> 00:11:40,431
So it's that connection, you see, to sit with this rotting corpse and to remind oneself that, well, you know, one day this is going to be like that.

98
00:11:41,892 --> 00:11:45,155
By the way, the commentaries tell people not to sit windward.

99
00:11:45,878 --> 00:11:49,022
That's obviously a bit of good advice.

100
00:11:50,203 --> 00:11:54,970
Now in this way, he abides contemplating the body both internally and externally, etc.

101
00:11:55,770 --> 00:12:07,546
And as though, again, as though he were to see a corpse thrown aside in the charnel ground devoured by crows, hawks, vultures, dogs, jackals, various kinds of worms.

102
00:12:08,326 --> 00:12:09,708
And again, this body

103
00:12:10,027 --> 00:12:13,870
This body too is of the same nature.

104
00:12:13,910 --> 00:12:14,792
It will be like that.

105
00:12:14,892 --> 00:12:19,636
It is not exempt from that fate.

106
00:12:19,657 --> 00:12:26,323
And as though he were to see a corpse thrown aside in the charnel ground, a skeleton with flesh and blood held together with sinews.

107
00:12:27,184 --> 00:12:31,288
A fleshless skeleton smeared with blood held together with sinews.

108
00:12:31,808 --> 00:12:35,393
A skeleton without flesh and blood held together with sinews.

109
00:12:35,861 --> 00:12:38,926
Disconnected bones scattered in all directions.

110
00:12:38,966 --> 00:12:55,528
Here a hand bone, there a foot bone, here a shin bone, there a thigh bone, here a hip bone, there a back bone, here a rib bone, there a breast bone, here an arm bone, there a shoulder bone, here a neck bone, there a jaw bone, here a tooth, there a skull.

111
00:12:56,049 --> 00:12:58,833
And the bhikkhu compares this same body with it thus.

112
00:12:58,974 --> 00:13:01,317
This body too is the same nature.

113
00:13:01,778 --> 00:13:02,960
It will be like that.

114
00:13:03,460 --> 00:13:05,363
It is not exempt from that fate.

115
00:13:06,658 --> 00:13:24,009
And then the final bit is a corpse thrown aside in the charnel grounds, bones bleached white, the color of shells, bones heaped up more than a year old, bones rotted and crumbled to dust.

116
00:13:24,479 --> 00:13:26,100
The Bhikkhu compares the same body.

117
00:13:26,500 --> 00:13:28,504
This body too is of the same nature.

118
00:13:28,543 --> 00:13:30,085
It will be like that.

119
00:13:30,566 --> 00:13:32,307
It is not exempt from that fate.

120
00:13:33,129 --> 00:13:36,172
So he's very big on death, the Buddha.

121
00:13:37,854 --> 00:13:49,407
I did, for those of you who are new to the evening, I did a whole section on death and the Buddha's teachings about death and how to do death contemplations in earlier videos.

122
00:13:49,927 --> 00:14:19,477
uh and but here uh it's really um really grinding our nose in in in the dirt you might say and you can see from his explanation that uh he's done it he's been there he's sat with this lot and he's and he's made those uh observations right so this comes from his own personal experience without any doubt um and uh i don't know if you've actually

123
00:14:19,778 --> 00:14:23,043
seen a dead body, but it is definitely lifeless.

124
00:14:23,803 --> 00:14:43,912
And when you go to the East as a Bhikkhu, as a monk or nun, you can go to the mortuary, you can go to the pathology department and see them cutting the body open and trying to find out why the person died, etc.

125
00:14:44,673 --> 00:14:47,878
And that's quite an experience.

126
00:14:48,466 --> 00:14:53,671
My first experience with a dead body actually goes back to when I was about the age of 10.

127
00:14:54,371 --> 00:15:01,480
My father, my great aunt Florence, which is a lovely First World War name, isn't it, Florence?

128
00:15:02,581 --> 00:15:05,984
She died and my father asked me if I want to come and see the body.

129
00:15:06,325 --> 00:15:09,707
I was a 10 year old, of course, that did sound like an adventure.

130
00:15:10,349 --> 00:15:15,975
And when we got there, she was laid out, you see, and I just remember touching a forehead here.

131
00:15:16,259 --> 00:15:25,707
And it was very cold or cool, you know, and it moved, you know, like I thought it'd be stiff, but it moved.

132
00:15:26,408 --> 00:15:30,633
And I don't remember being particularly upset by it or anything like that.

133
00:15:30,653 --> 00:15:32,014
It was just a dead body.

134
00:15:34,056 --> 00:15:41,663
But the next time I had an occasion with a dead body was I was at the Buddhist Sahara.

135
00:15:42,344 --> 00:15:44,645
I was already ordained actually, it was my first year.

136
00:15:45,097 --> 00:15:48,023
And I was at the Vihara in Birmingham, that's where I was staying.

137
00:15:48,644 --> 00:15:54,354
And we had a visit from some Christian monks from the St. Bernard's Abbey, which is near Birmingham.

138
00:15:54,474 --> 00:15:58,902
And they were picking up Tibetan monks who were staying with us.

139
00:15:59,823 --> 00:16:10,261
And it was part of this communication, you might say, between monks of different, well, between the Buddhist and the Christian monks.

140
00:16:11,102 --> 00:16:17,092
And he was an elderly man and he got hold of this huge case and carried out his car.

141
00:16:17,514 --> 00:16:22,503
As I came out from the gate, he was falling to the ground, calling for assistance, you see.

142
00:16:23,004 --> 00:16:26,308
So I put the bags down and ran over to him.

143
00:16:26,369 --> 00:16:31,057
And so I held him as he was lying down on the ground, you see.

144
00:16:31,778 --> 00:16:35,946
And he lost consciousness.

145
00:16:36,279 --> 00:16:40,024
And then he made this huge effort to come back, his eyes open and he's trying to come back.

146
00:16:40,563 --> 00:16:42,306
And then he just let go.

147
00:16:42,806 --> 00:16:46,190
And the weight of the body was quite obvious to me.

148
00:16:47,070 --> 00:16:55,778
I was thinking it's rather ironic that this wonderful Christian monk died with a Buddhist head as his last vision.

149
00:16:56,679 --> 00:17:01,403
And then the ambulance came 10 minutes later, but he was gone.

150
00:17:02,304 --> 00:17:06,169
So when we have an occasion

151
00:17:06,487 --> 00:17:08,470
to be with somebody who's dying.

152
00:17:09,411 --> 00:17:11,073
This is a real teaching for us.

153
00:17:11,113 --> 00:17:15,679
I mean, that sounds a bit callous almost.

154
00:17:15,699 --> 00:17:20,105
I mean, you're there for the person who's dying, of course, but it does bring it to you.

155
00:17:20,766 --> 00:17:30,557
And to observe anything that's died, your pet that's died, that can be also quite a teaching too.

156
00:17:31,219 --> 00:17:35,785
Or anything that you see on the road that's been run over by a car.

157
00:17:36,118 --> 00:17:45,409
That also is a teaching of this finality, of this disappearance of the person.

158
00:17:45,808 --> 00:17:49,853
And what you're left with is, well, just a bag of bones, really.

159
00:17:50,713 --> 00:17:54,417
So something that it's good to contemplate.

160
00:17:54,617 --> 00:17:57,260
Now, I do it every day this evening.

161
00:17:57,922 --> 00:18:00,944
I do the reflections on sickness, aging and death.

162
00:18:01,076 --> 00:18:12,710
It only takes a moment, but it just puts that sort of reality back in life, you know, that everything is coming to an end.

163
00:18:13,371 --> 00:18:19,657
And quite paradoxically, you think you get depressed if you brought that to mind.

164
00:18:20,118 --> 00:18:27,928
But of course, it brings you into the present moment and the sheer miracle of being here, the sheer miracle of being awake, of being aware.

165
00:18:28,464 --> 00:18:31,367
And the effort then is to make the most of it.

166
00:18:32,229 --> 00:18:38,114
So the contemplation of death, however you do it, has great benefits.

167
00:18:38,575 --> 00:18:44,400
And also, of course, in the final hour, we remind ourselves, my mother died, my father died.

168
00:18:44,441 --> 00:18:46,382
Everybody's been there.

169
00:18:46,402 --> 00:18:47,644
The Buddha died, for heaven's sake.

170
00:18:49,404 --> 00:18:51,667
And that gives you the courage to go through the gate.

171
00:18:53,209 --> 00:18:56,311
So, yes.

172
00:18:56,848 --> 00:19:23,565
do contemplation of sickness aging and death at least for a little moment every day so i can only hope my words have been of some assistance that have not created too much confusion and that by your practice you will be liberated more suffering sooner rather than later uh just in case i forget by the way all those of you who've joined because of the uh

173
00:19:24,912 --> 00:19:33,429
The guy, of course, you are, of course, welcome to join me every evening because this will go on until the end of lockdown, whenever that is.

174
00:19:34,290 --> 00:19:36,214
I'm hoping it won't be next year, that's all.

175
00:19:37,637 --> 00:19:38,078
Very good.

176
00:19:38,159 --> 00:19:40,743
So I'll start with the Refugees and Precepts.

